              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13244359-donna?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2571980226" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11932416979179570121">I&apos;ve read many Grisham novels and have enjoyed the first several. And I&apos;ve have even read one recently....last week to be more accurate. In that review, I couldn&apos;t quite name the thing that kept me from liking it like I&apos;ve liked his older stuff. But now after reading this one, I think I know what that &quot;thing&quot; is. <br/><br/>Grisham can come up with a story...that isn&apos;t a problem. He can create suspicion and suspense. Great. But the problem I&apos;ve had with this book and with the one I read last week, is the w</span>
  <span id="freeText11932416979179570121" style="display:none">I've read many Grisham novels and have enjoyed the first several. And I've have even read one recently....last week to be more accurate. In that review, I couldn't quite name the thing that kept me from liking it like I've liked his older stuff. But now after reading this one, I think I know what that "thing" is. <br /><br />Grisham can come up with a story...that isn't a problem. He can create suspicion and suspense. Great. But the problem I've had with this book and with the one I read last week, is the writing. There is so much telling. He explains everything. It feels like he sees the scene in his head, and writes exactly what he sees. Nothing more. Nothing less. That is why I'm having a problem with the characters. They feel like cardboard....like they are in a painting and I'm trying to guess, who they really are, what they are thinking and feeling, etc. <br /><br />Also, this book was predictable in the "what really happened" arena. My advice, read the first part to get the info on the crisis at hand....then skip right to the very end. I promise. It will be okay. </span>
  <a data-text-id="11932416979179570121" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


